    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-02-26T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-02-26T06:00:00-05:00" n="3"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d3">
                <head>3. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Office of the High Commissioner for
                        Austria</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d3fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 663.001/2–2655. Top Secret; Priority. Repeated to London, Paris, and
                        Moscow eyes only for the Ambassadors.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Vienna</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1955-02-26T12:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 26, 1955—noon</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1882. Eyes only Acting Secretary and <persName corresp="#p_MLT1"
                        >Merchant</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName> has
                    informed Western High Commissioners in strictest confidence as follows:</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> yesterday asked <persName
                        corresp="#p_BN1">Bischoff</persName> to come to see him and elaborated his
                    views on Austrian question asking that Austrian Government inform no one of this
                    approach. He explained that Soviet Union did not demand total agreement on
                    German question but wanted security that Anschluss would not take place now or
                    in future. How this was to be accomplished was not explained but he did say that
                    if this was achieved Austrian treaty could be concluded and evacuation carried
                    out immediately. <persName corresp="#p_BN1">Bischoff</persName>’s brief message
                    did not explain what next step was to be. Presumably Soviets are softening up
                    Austrians to support some Soviet initiative with Western Powers. <persName
                        corresp="#p_FL1">Figl</persName> hopes receive further information and to
                    discuss matter with <persName>Raab</persName>, who is out of town, on
                    Monday.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TLE1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Thompson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
